      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Here's the implementation of the `check_permission` function that meets the requirements:\n```python\ndef check_permission(user, resource, action):\n    if user.role == 'admin':\n        return True\n    elif user.role == 'editor':\n        return user.user_id == resource.owner_id or user.role == 'admin'\n    elif user.role == 'viewer':\n        return user.user_id == resource.owner_id or user.role == 'admin'\n```\nThis function works by first checking if the user is an admin. If they are, it immediately returns `True`, regardless of the action they try to perform. If the user is not an admin, it checks if the user has permissions to perform the action based on their role and whether they own the resource. If the user is an editor, they can edit their own resource or edit resources owned by admins. If the user is a viewer, they can view their own resource or view resources owned by admins.\n\nYou can run the test suite again with this implementation, and it should pass all the tests.",
